Welcome to the wild, wacky universe of Haplopraxis, where we’ve taken the phrase “knowledge is power” and cranked it up to eleven. Literally. You see, in our grand design, we’ve replaced your mundane twelve-hour clocks with an eleven-hour clock—because, why not? Eleven letters in the name means we need to mess with time in the most confusing way possible.

Here’s where it gets juicy: knowledge is doubling faster than a kid at a candy store, and by 2042, it’ll be doubling every 12 seconds. Forget the speed of light; we’re diving into logarithmic impulse travel. Want to zoom around the universe like a caffeinated squirrel? Just hold down the F5 key and watch time bend to your will—or at least until the universe resets every January 1, 2400, because who doesn’t love a fresh start every year?

Oh, and don’t even think about hitting the G key. That’s the global reset button, and if you press it, everyone will know you’re a no-good troublemaker. You’ll be marked as a red dot on the map, making you the most popular target for everyone’s mining lasers. But hey, at least you can still zip around with autoblink—because what’s a cosmic adventure without a bit of cheeky teleportation?

We’ve also cooked up a delightful minigame called Spherepop, where you can practice your typing skills by popping bubbles, earning points to buy precious texture crystals and time crystals—because what else would you want to do with your time? Just don’t get too comfortable; you’ll need to visit 200,000 stars before those coveted texture crystals become available, turning exploration into a glorified cosmic scavenger hunt.

And if you thought we’d leave out some ancient history, think again! We’re throwing in Cistercian numerals because who doesn’t want to decode medieval math while dodging laser beams? Your resource management skills will be put to the test as you navigate the complexities of numeral systems from centuries past—talk about a way to spice up your intergalactic journey!

So, grab your ship, ready your flight mode signature, and prepare for a game that’s less about practicality and more about the absurdity of it all. Haplopraxis isn’t just a game; it’s an exercise in embracing chaos with a sprinkle of educational flair, all while you try to figure out why on earth you agreed to such an elaborate setup in the first place. Good luck, spacefarer—you’re going to need it!
